# Update ktail

```java
ktail = head;
```

This is very important.

Before reversing, `head` was the first node of the group.

After reversing, that same node becomes the tail.

Example:

```text
Before reversing:
head = 3

3 -> 4
```

After reversing:

```text
4 -> 3
     ^
   ktail
```

So:

```java
ktail = head;
```

means the old group head is now the tail of the reversed group.

---

# Move to Next Group

```java
head = ptr;
```

After checking `k` nodes, `ptr` points to the next group start.

Example:

```text
Before:
1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5

After checking first group of k = 2:
ptr = 3
```

So:

```java
head = ptr;
```

means the next group starts at `3`.

---

# Attach Remaining Nodes

```java
if (ktail != null) {
    ktail.next = head;
}
```

This connects leftover nodes that are fewer than `k`.

Example:

```text
head = 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
k = 2
```

After reversing full groups:

```text
2 -> 1 -> 4 -> 3
```

Remaining node:

```text
5
```

At the end:

```java
ktail.next = head;
```

connects:

```text
3.next = 5
```

Final:

```text
2 -> 1 -> 4 -> 3 -> 5
```

---

# Return Answer

```java
return newHead == null ? head : newHead;
```

If at least one group was reversed, `newHead` stores the answer head.

If no group was reversed, return the original `head`.

Example:

```text
head = 1 -> 2
k = 3
```

There are not enough nodes to reverse.

So `newHead` stays `null`.

Return original head:

```text
1 -> 2
```

